fifth toe","Medial aspect of the leg and medial malleolus","Anterior thigh and knee, medial lower leg","Posterior aspect of the calf and heel","Lateral aspect of the leg and dorsum of foot"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial aspect of the leg and medial malleolus\u003C/strong\u003E is innervated by the L4 dermatome. This forms an important anatomical landmark for testing L4 nerve root function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent other dermatomes:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral border of the foot and fifth toe\u003C/strong\u003E is supplied by the S1 dermatome\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior thigh and knee, medial lower leg \u003C/strong\u003Eis primarily supplied by L3\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior aspect of the calf and heel\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily supplied by S2\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral aspect of the leg and dorsum of foot\u003C/strong\u003E represents the L5 dermatome\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding dermatome distributions is crucial for localising neurological lesions and determining the level of nerve root involvement in conditions such as disc herniation or radiculopathy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The L4 dermatome includes the medial leg and medial malleolus","The L5 dermatome includes the lateral leg and dorsum of foot","The S1 dermatome includes the lateral foot and lateral fifth toe"],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cDermatomes radiculaires humains\u201d by CYP3A42D6 is licensed under\u00a0Creative Commons\u00a0Attribution-Share Alike 4.0 Unported\u00a